Predicting Future Traffic Volume¶

Introduction:

This data set contains hourly information regarding traffic volume and weather conditions on a highway between Minneapolis and St. Paul, Minnesota. The data set can be obtained at: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Metro+Interstate+Traffic+Volume. The goal of this project is to apply deep learning to do time series forecasting. Specifically, given a 6-hour input window, this project will attempt to predict the traffic volume 2 hours/time steps into the future using several different recurrent neural network (RNN) architectures.

Import libraries and read in file:

In [1]:

There are three categorical variables (holiday, weather_main, and weather_description), one ordinal/interval variable (date_time), and five numeric variables (temp, rain_1h, snow_1h, clouds_all, and traffic_volume) including the target variable, traffic_volume. The date_time variable is in string format, and thus needs to be converted to an appropriate data type.

Convert date_time variable to correct format:

In [5]:
traffic['date_time'] = pd.to_datetime(traffic['date_time'])

Engineer features by separating date_time variable into Month, Day of the Week, and Hour:

In [6]:
traffic['month'] = traffic['date_time'].dt.month
traffic['day_of_week'] = traffic['date_time'].dt.dayofweek
traffic['hour'] = traffic['date_time'].dt.hour

Drop date_time, holiday, and weather_description:

  • date_time is adequately captured by the features engineered from this variable
  • holiday does not seem useful as it only identifies 1 hour of every 24-hour time period it actually is supposed to capture
  • weather_description too highly correlated with weather_main
In [18]:
# drop date_time, holiday, and weather_description

Split the Data into Training and Test sets:

In [22]:
train = traffic[0:43204]
test = traffic[43204:48204]  # last 5,000 observations for test set

Normalize the Data:

  • Here, the feature variables must be normalized separately from the target variable. This way, it will be much easier to denormalize the target predictions for the test set later on.

  • Hour variable not normalized in order to give more weight to this variable in the models, as it is the most indicative feature of traffic_volume

In [23]:
feat_columns = ['temp', 'rain_1h', 'snow_1h','clouds_all', 'month', 'day_of_week']

feat_transformer = MinMaxScaler()
traf_transformer = MinMaxScaler()

feat_transformer = feat_transformer.fit(train[feat_columns].to_numpy())
traf_transformer = traf_transformer.fit(train[['traffic_volume']])

train.loc[:, feat_columns] = feat_transformer.transform(train[feat_columns].to_numpy())
train['traffic_volume'] = traf_transformer.transform(train[['traffic_volume']])

test.loc[:, feat_columns] = feat_transformer.transform(test[feat_columns].to_numpy())
test['traffic_volume'] = traf_transformer.transform(test[['traffic_volume']])

Create X and Y Datasets:

In [24]:
# create X and Y from training set:
y_train = train['traffic_volume']
x_train = train.drop(['traffic_volume'], axis=1)

# create X and Y from test set:
y_test = test['traffic_volume']
x_test = test.drop(['traffic_volume'], axis =1)

Create Function to Transform Datasets into Proper Format for TensorFlow Keras:

  • function to iterate through dataset based on time steps/window (6 hours) and target step size (2 hours into the future)
  • returns arrays in format: [samples, timesteps, features] and [samples, ] for X and Y, respectively
In [25]:
def create_dataset(X, y, time_step = 6, target_step = 2):
  Xs, ys = [], []  
  for i in range(len(X) - (time_step + (target_step-1))): # iterate through range based on length of dataset and time step/target step sizes
    dist = X.iloc[i: (i + time_step)].to_numpy() # calculate windows
    Xs.append(dist)
    ys.append(y.iloc[i + time_step + (target_step-1)]) # find corresponding target (y value) for each window
  return np.array(Xs), np.array(ys)

Transform Train and Test Datasets into [samples, timesteps, features] and [samples, ] formats for TensorFlow Keras:

In [26]:
X_train, Y_train = create_dataset(x_train, y_train, 6, 2)

X_test, Y_test = create_dataset(x_test, y_test, 6, 2)

Create Bidirectional LSTM Model -- BEST MODEL¶

In [32]:
model2 = models.Sequential([
                            layers.Bidirectional(layers.LSTM(256, return_sequences = True)),
                            layers.Dropout(0.4),
                            layers.LSTM(128, return_sequences = True),
                            layers.Dropout(0.2),
                            layers.LSTM(64, return_sequences = True),
                            layers.Dropout(0.2),
                            layers.LSTM(32, return_sequences = False),
                            layers.Dense(1)
])
In [33]:
# Learning rate/exponential decay schedule & early stopping:

lr_sched = tf.keras.optimizers.schedules.ExponentialDecay(0.001, decay_steps=100000, decay_rate=0.96, staircase=True)

early_stopping = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, mode='min')
In [34]:
model2.compile(loss= 'mean_absolute_error', optimizer=tf.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr_sched))
In [35]:
history2 = model2.fit(X_train, Y_train, validation_data=(X_test, Y_test), epochs=50, batch_size=212, callbacks=[early_stopping])

Combine CNN with RNN¶

In [38]:
model3 = models.Sequential([
                            layers.Conv1D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
                            layers.LSTM(64),
                            layers.Dropout(0.1),
                            layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'),
                            layers.Dense(10, activation='relu'),
                            layers.Dense(1, activation='relu')
])
In [39]:
# Early stopping:
